Decided to try the competition to Malecon which is across the street. Chicken is grilled here, not rotisserie, and unfortunately results in dry and tough meat, particularly the breast. My serving was inconsistently heated, with some pieces cold and some hot, indicating it had been cooked (who knows how much) earlier and reheated. Service was adequate if somewhat inattentive. The restaurant itself is lazily kept with the bar used as a storage area, over crowded with chairs and tables, and overall unappealing. There's a reason Malecon is consistently packed and this restaurant isn't.  2 stars as the pieces of chicken that were hot and not dry as jerky were quite tasty.

Pros: food was good, restaurant looks nice, staff was accommodating of a walk-in party of 8 and fine with splitting checks.  Middling: Some reasonably priced options but the rest of the menu is very pricy and for some reason a lot of Italian/steakhouse inspiration which wasn't apparent until we sat down.  Cons: People who arrived after us (mind, they were not busy when we arrived) received their food before us. Our food starts to come out, a little staggered but okay. The last two, just simple sandwiches, took another 15 mins after the last plate. Everyone tried to wait/eat slow, but we were all getting full by the time their food came. And then the real wait began. It was 655 at the latest when all our plates were taken away. We proceeded to be ignored for the next 20 minutes while the restaurant started to get busier... you'd think they'd want to get the table flipped. At one point (maybe 710?) we saw our waiter rolling napkins around flatware - not exactly the most pressing task. Finally got back to us, but it was another 10 minutes to get the checks, and another 10 after that for him to come back with our cash/receipts. We didn't get out until almost 740.  They got an automatic gratuity out of us as a large party, which is expected, but time is money, what the hell were they thinking??

The Worst Service, at first I thought it was fluke. I gave this place three chances. The first time we went. The rice was over cooked, I asked for a steak medium rare they gave it to me well done. When I told the waitress she told me that's medium. So I guess well done is burnt...  Second time My wife wanted to go I was apprehensive. I went anyway, The place was full so we had to wait which I don't have an issue. What I have an issue is trying to let anyone know that we are waiting to be seated. They have no one that keeps track of the people are waiting. So a couple behind us got seated, when I told them we have been waiting they said oh the place is full you have to wait... If you had some time of organization then you would know who was waiting first.  Today, was the last time we didn't wait this time to even be seated. There was a nice couple of ladies that got seated then I am standing there next to the Kiosk waiting for one of these so called servers to come over. I asked one of the waitresses if someone is doing the seating. Again she told me we are full you have to wait... I didn't ask you that I asked who is taking care of the seating... Sigh..  So 10 minutes pass by and a group of 5 (we are 4) come in and a table opens up and they start to seat them. I had it I told them off and we left.  Went across the street To Malecon, What a difference, they were way more busy than El Conde. But are way more organized, there is a wait line where they advise you how long and put in a queue. They said 30 minutes, but it was only 20. I Did not mind the wait and the food in my humble opinion is way better, less greasy and they know how to cook a steak.  So if you find El conde full good luck, you are better off going to Malecon much better service by 10 fold.

I don't speak Spanish which immediately cast me as an outsider but that's ok!  The service suffered slightly as a result but the steak and side dishes were well worth the sassy attitude I encountered from the my waitress.  The servings are huge and the steak was tender, juicy and so succulent.  Worth the $15 for the Curasco y Camarón or Surf & Turf Steak & Shrimp dinner.  I highly recommend splurging and getting a side of the sweet Monfongo (friend plantains)  They are best described as a smoky indulgence on par with a find whiskey & cigar!
I ate at this establishment last night, while the steak was good the shrimp was burnt! Also the bathroom NEEDED attending and our service wasn't to par either.
